Aug 29 2006 	Rushmore is Great	I was very pleased with this budget hotel. I am a small, middle-aged woman travelling alone, who does not eat breakfast. With that in mind, here's what I thought:My room (#4) was small, but not the closet I've found in other budget hotels. It had a little desk, and a little vanity table, and with the draperies and the wall-painting, it was a very pleasant place to sit in. The bathroom was tiny, but absolutely perfect. It was completely tiled in marble with a nice little shelf to put toiletries on. The shower was the smallest I've ever seen (beware you who are over six feet or very heavy), but the water pressure was excellent and there was plenty of hot water--two things which in my experience are seldom to be found in English showers.The staff was friendly and helpful; I didn't actually ask them for much, but I saw them helping other people and was struck by how often they volunteered to do something instead of waiting to be asked. I also liked the fact that there was someone at the desk all through the night. Internet is available for a pound fifty; fifty pence more than at some commercials places, and worth it for the convenience. I sometimes also found wireless access available in my room. The room was cleaned and neatened nicely every day. Oh, and there were extra pillows. Phone worked fine at 20 p. a call.Caveats: This is a budget hotel, not a Holiday Inn kind of place. It does not have those kinds of amenities. There is no lift and nobody to carry your bags. And the breakfast is not English, i.e., they are not cooking you eggs and bacon and blood pudding. The one day I made it down, the dining room was very pleasant (as was the small adjacent lounge), and fresh coffee and tea were liberally and quickly supplied. There were cereals, yogurt, juices and toast, as well as some cold cuts and slices of what looked to be American cheese.For the money, I was very happy indeed with the Rushmore.	
